{
  "Most oxygen in the blood (~98.5%) is transported:": "",
  "Bound to hemoglobin as oxyhemoglobin (HbO₂)": "",
  "Bound to plasma albumin": "",
  "Dissolved directly in the plasma": "",
  "As bicarbonate ions": "",
  "Approximately 98.5% of oxygen in the blood is bound to hemoglobin within red blood cells, forming oxyhemoglobin. Only about 1.5% is dissolved directly in plasma.": "",
  "Each hemoglobin molecule can bind up to how many oxygen molecules?": "",
  "2": "",
  "8": "",
  "4": "",
  "1": "",
  "Each hemoglobin molecule contains four heme groups, each with an iron atom that can reversibly bind one O₂ molecule. When all four sites are occupied, hemoglobin is said to be 100% saturated.": "",
  "The shape of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve is:": "",
  "Exponential": "",
  "Linear": "",
  "Flat": "",
  "Sigmoidal (S-shaped)": "",
  "The S-shaped (sigmoidal) curve reflects cooperative binding — once the first O₂ molecule binds, the hemoglobin molecule undergoes a conformational change that makes it easier for subsequent O₂ molecules to bind (and vice versa for unloading).": "",
  "A right shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve indicates that hemoglobin:": "",
  "Releases oxygen more readily to the tissues": "",
  "Holds oxygen more tightly": "",
  "Cannot bind oxygen at all": "",
  "Has no change in oxygen affinity": "",
  "A right shift means hemoglobin has reduced affinity for O₂, so it unloads oxygen more easily. This is beneficial for active tissues that need more oxygen, such as exercising muscles.": "",
  "Factors that cause a right shift of the O₂-Hb dissociation curve include:": "",
  "Decreased temperature, increased pH, decreased CO₂": "",
  "Only decreased CO₂": "",
  "Increased temperature, decreased pH, increased CO₂, and increased 2,3-BPG": "",
  "Only cold temperatures": "",
  "Active tissues produce heat, CO₂, and acid (H⁺), all of which shift the curve rightward. Red blood cells also produce 2,3-BPG during glycolysis, which binds to deoxyhemoglobin and further promotes O₂ release.": "",
  "The majority of CO₂ (~70%) is transported in the blood as:": "",
  "Dissolved CO₂ gas in plasma": "",
  "Carbaminohemoglobin": "",
  "Bicarbonate ions (HCO₃⁻) in the plasma": "",
  "About 70% of CO₂ entering the blood is converted to bicarbonate ions inside red blood cells by the enzyme carbonic anhydrase (CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻). The HCO₃⁻ then moves into the plasma for transport.": "",
  "About 23% of CO₂ is transported bound to hemoglobin as:": "",
  "Methemoglobin (oxidized iron in the ferric Fe3+ state)": "",
  "Carbaminohemoglobin (CO₂ bound to the globin protein's amino groups)": "",
  "Carboxyhemoglobin (CO bound to the heme iron group)": "",
  "Oxyhemoglobin (O₂ bound to the heme iron group)": "",
  "Carbaminohemoglobin forms when CO₂ binds to amino acid residues on the globin portion (not the heme groups) of hemoglobin. This is distinct from carboxyhemoglobin, which is hemoglobin bound to carbon monoxide.": "",
  "The enzyme carbonic anhydrase catalyzes which reaction inside red blood cells?": "",
  "CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻": "",
  "Hemoglobin synthesis from amino acids": "",
  "O₂ binding to hemoglobin": "",
  "Surfactant production from phospholipids": "",
  "Carbonic anhydrase rapidly catalyzes the conversion of CO₂ and water into carbonic acid (H₂CO₃), which immediately dissociates into hydrogen ions (H⁺) and bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻). This reaction is essential for CO₂ transport and acid-base balance.": "",
  "Carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning is life-threatening because CO:": "",
  "Destroys hemoglobin permanently": "",
  "Is acidic and lowers blood pH to lethal levels": "",
  "Directly poisons mitochondria without affecting hemoglobin": "",
  "Binds to hemoglobin with approximately 200-250 times greater affinity than O₂, blocking O₂ transport": "",
  "Carbon monoxide binds to the same heme iron sites as O₂ but with roughly 200-250 times greater affinity. Once CO occupies hemoglobin (forming carboxyhemoglobin), it prevents O₂ binding and also shifts the O₂-Hb curve leftward, impairing O₂ release to tissues.": "",
  "Normal oxygen saturation (SpO₂) measured by pulse oximetry is:": "",
  "100% at all times": "",
  "85-90%": "",
  "≥95%": "",
  "70-80%": "",
  "Normal SpO₂ is 95% or higher, indicating that hemoglobin is well-saturated with oxygen. Values below 90% are generally considered clinically significant hypoxemia and often warrant supplemental oxygen therapy.": "",
  "What is the Bohr effect?": "",
  "The process by which fetal hemoglobin preferentially binds oxygen over adult hemoglobin": "",
  "The principle that gas pressure and volume are inversely proportional": "",
  "The conversion of CO₂ to bicarbonate by carbonic anhydrase": "",
  "The phenomenon in which increased CO₂ and decreased pH reduce hemoglobin's affinity for O₂, promoting O₂ release to active tissues": "",
  "The Bohr effect describes how elevated CO₂ and hydrogen ions (lower pH) in metabolically active tissues cause a conformational change in hemoglobin that decreases its O₂ affinity, facilitating O₂ unloading precisely where it is needed most.": "",
  "What is the chloride shift?": "",
  "The active transport of chloride across the alveolar membrane during gas exchange": "",
  "The movement of chloride into red blood cells as bicarbonate moves out, maintaining electrical neutrality": "",
  "The release of chloride from hemoglobin when O₂ binds": "",
  "The destruction of chloride ions in the plasma during respiration": "",
  "When HCO₃⁻ exits the red blood cell into the plasma, Cl⁻ ions enter through the band 3 anion exchanger to maintain electrical balance across the cell membrane. This process, called the chloride shift (or Hamburger phenomenon), accompanies CO₂ loading in the tissues.": "",
  "What is 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)?": "",
  "A type of surfactant found in the alveoli": "",
  "A hormone produced by the lungs to regulate breathing": "",
  "A metabolic intermediate produced during glycolysis in red blood cells that binds to deoxyhemoglobin and promotes O₂ release": "",
  "An enzyme that catalyzes O₂ binding to hemoglobin": "",
  "2,3-BPG is a byproduct of red blood cell glycolysis that inserts into the central cavity of deoxyhemoglobin, stabilizing its low-affinity state and promoting further O₂ unloading. Its levels increase in conditions of chronic hypoxia, such as living at high altitude.": "",
  "What is oxyhemoglobin?": "",
  "Hemoglobin bound to carbon dioxide": "",
  "Hemoglobin that has oxygen molecules bound to its heme groups": "",
  "A form of hemoglobin found only in fetal blood": "",
  "Hemoglobin that has been oxidized and cannot carry any gas": "",
  "Oxyhemoglobin (HbO₂) is the oxygenated form of hemoglobin, with one or more O₂ molecules bound to its heme iron atoms. It appears bright red and is found predominantly in arterial blood leaving the lungs.": "",
  "What is cyanosis?": "",
  "Pale skin caused by anemia": "",
  "A bluish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes caused by a significant increase in deoxygenated hemoglobin in the blood": "",
  "A yellowish skin color caused by excess bilirubin": "",
  "A reddish skin flush caused by excess oxygenated blood": "",
  "Cyanosis occurs when there is 5 g/dL or more of deoxyhemoglobin in the capillary blood. Deoxyhemoglobin has a dark blue-purple color, which shows through the skin and is most easily visible in the lips, nail beds, and earlobes.": "",
  "What is fetal hemoglobin (HbF)?": "",
  "A form of hemoglobin present in the fetus that has a higher affinity for O₂ than adult hemoglobin, allowing the fetus to extract O₂ from maternal blood": "",
  "A defective form of hemoglobin that causes sickle cell disease": "",
  "An inactive precursor of adult hemoglobin that does not transport gases": "",
  "Hemoglobin that only carries CO₂ in fetal circulation": "",
  "Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) contains gamma globin chains instead of the beta chains found in adult hemoglobin (HbA). HbF has a higher oxygen affinity (left-shifted curve) because it does not bind 2,3-BPG as effectively, allowing the fetus to extract O₂ from maternal blood at the placenta.": "",
  "What does 'cooperative binding' mean in the context of hemoglobin?": "",
  "Multiple hemoglobin molecules working together to transport O₂": "",
  "The binding of one O₂ molecule to hemoglobin increases the affinity of the remaining binding sites for additional O₂ molecules": "",
  "Hemoglobin cooperating with myoglobin to transfer O₂ to muscles": "",
  "Red blood cells aggregating to increase total O₂ carrying capacity": "",
  "Cooperative binding means that when the first O₂ molecule binds to one of hemoglobin's four subunits, it induces a conformational change that increases the affinity of the remaining subunits for O₂. This produces the characteristic sigmoidal shape of the O₂-Hb dissociation curve.": "",
  "What does 'carboxyhemoglobin' mean?": "",
  "A normal breakdown product of hemoglobin metabolism": "",
  "Hemoglobin that has been converted to bicarbonate": "",
  "Hemoglobin bound to carbon dioxide on the globin chain": "",
  "Hemoglobin in which carbon monoxide (CO) occupies the O₂-binding sites on the heme groups, rendering them unable to carry oxygen": "",
  "Carboxyhemoglobin (HbCO) is formed when carbon monoxide binds to hemoglobin's heme iron — the same site where O₂ normally binds. Because CO's affinity is ~200-250 times that of O₂, it effectively locks out oxygen, making carboxyhemoglobin unable to participate in O₂ transport.": "",
  "What is pulse oximetry?": "",
  "An imaging technique that visualizes blood flow in the pulmonary arteries": "",
  "A spirometry test that measures oxygen flow rates": "",
  "A noninvasive method that uses light absorption through a finger or earlobe to estimate the percentage of hemoglobin saturated with oxygen (SpO₂)": "",
  "An invasive test requiring arterial blood draw to measure oxygen tension": "",
  "Pulse oximetry uses two wavelengths of light (red and infrared) passing through a pulsating vascular bed to measure the ratio of oxyhemoglobin to total hemoglobin. It provides a continuous, noninvasive estimate of arterial oxygen saturation.": "",
  "What does 'P50' mean on the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve?": "",
  "The total partial pressure of all gases in the blood": "",
  "The PO₂ at which hemoglobin is 50% saturated with oxygen (normally ~26.6 mmHg)": "",
  "The maximum PO₂ that hemoglobin can achieve": "",
  "The PO₂ at which hemoglobin is 100% saturated": "",
  "P50 is the partial pressure of oxygen at which hemoglobin is 50% saturated. The normal P50 is approximately 26.6 mmHg. An increased P50 (right shift) indicates decreased O₂ affinity, while a decreased P50 (left shift) indicates increased affinity.": "",
  "A firefighter is rescued from a burning building and is found confused and disoriented. His skin appears cherry red. Despite a pulse oximeter reading of 98%, the emergency physician orders a blood test for carboxyhemoglobin levels, which come back at 35%. Why was the pulse oximeter reading misleading?": "",
  "Standard pulse oximeters cannot distinguish between oxyhemoglobin and carboxyhemoglobin because both absorb light similarly, giving a falsely normal SpO₂ reading": "",
  "Carbon monoxide increases true oxygen saturation by enhancing the hemoglobin molecule's affinity for oxygen molecules at the tissue level": "",
  "The pulse oximeter sensor malfunctions in hot environments because elevated skin temperature disrupts the infrared light absorption readings": "",
  "The cherry-red skin color indicates adequate oxygenation because it reflects a high concentration of oxyhemoglobin in the peripheral capillary beds": "",
  "Standard pulse oximeters measure light absorption at two wavelengths and cannot differentiate carboxyhemoglobin (HbCO) from oxyhemoglobin (HbO₂) because they absorb light similarly. This gives a falsely reassuring SpO₂ reading despite severe CO poisoning, which is why CO-oximetry or blood gas analysis is essential.": "",
  "A marathon runner's muscles are producing large amounts of CO₂, lactic acid, and heat during a race. His sports medicine physician explains that these conditions actually benefit oxygen delivery to the muscles. Which physiological mechanism explains why O₂ is delivered more efficiently to exercising muscles?": "",
  "Blood flow completely bypasses the lungs during intense exercise": "",
  "Exercising muscles actively pump O₂ out of hemoglobin": "",
  "The Bohr effect — increased CO₂, decreased pH, and elevated temperature shift the O₂-Hb curve rightward, promoting greater O₂ unloading at the tissues": "",
  "The lungs produce extra hemoglobin during exercise": "",
  "The Bohr effect is a built-in feedback mechanism: the metabolic byproducts of active tissues (CO₂, H⁺, and heat) decrease hemoglobin's O₂ affinity. This rightward shift of the O₂-Hb curve ensures that more oxygen is released precisely in the tissues that need it most.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease has a hemoglobin level of 7 g/dL (normal: 12-17 g/dL). She feels constantly fatigued and short of breath even at rest. Her PaO₂ is normal at 95 mmHg. Why is she still experiencing symptoms of oxygen deficiency?": "",
  "Carbon monoxide produced as a byproduct of her kidney disease is accumulating in the blood and blocking hemoglobin from binding oxygen molecules at the alveolar level": "",
  "Her blood pH is too alkalotic for hemoglobin to bind oxygen effectively, causing a severe left shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve": "",
  "Although gas exchange is normal, she has fewer hemoglobin molecules to carry O₂, so total oxygen-carrying capacity is severely reduced despite normal PaO₂": "",
  "Her lungs are not functioning properly because the chronic kidney disease has caused pulmonary fibrosis and thickening of the respiratory membrane": "",
  "With severe anemia (low hemoglobin), the lungs are oxygenating the blood normally (normal PaO₂), but there are far fewer hemoglobin molecules to carry that oxygen. The total O₂ content of the blood is drastically reduced, which is why tissues become hypoxic despite adequate gas exchange.": "",
  "A pregnant woman's obstetrician explains that the fetus is able to extract oxygen from her blood at the placenta because of a difference in hemoglobin types. Why can fetal blood take up oxygen from maternal blood?": "",
  "The mother's hemoglobin cannot bind O₂, so all available O₂ goes to the fetus": "",
  "Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) has a higher O₂ affinity than maternal hemoglobin (HbA), so it can bind O₂ at the lower PO₂ present in the placenta": "",
  "Fetal blood has a much higher pH that forces O₂ transfer": "",
  "The placenta actively pumps O₂ from maternal to fetal blood": "",
  "Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) has a left-shifted O₂-Hb curve due to its reduced affinity for 2,3-BPG. This higher O₂ affinity allows HbF to pick up oxygen at the relatively low PO₂ of the placenta, effectively drawing O₂ away from the mother's hemoglobin.": "",
  "A patient in the ICU has a PaO₂ of 60 mmHg. The physician tells the team that at this level, hemoglobin saturation begins to drop rapidly with any further decrease in PO₂. Looking at the O₂-Hb dissociation curve, why does saturation plummet below this point?": "",
  "The lungs stop functioning below this oxygen level because the alveolar epithelial cells cannot survive when the partial pressure drops below 60 mmHg": "",
  "The sigmoidal shape of the curve means that below ~60 mmHg (on the steep portion), small decreases in PO₂ cause large drops in saturation due to cooperative unloading": "",
  "Below 60 mmHg, hemoglobin molecules are destroyed by the low oxygen environment, causing irreversible denaturation of the globin protein chains": "",
  "Below 60 mmHg, CO₂ molecules competitively displace all O₂ from hemoglobin binding sites because CO₂ has a higher affinity for the heme group at low pressures": "",
  "The O₂-Hb dissociation curve has a relatively flat upper portion (above ~60 mmHg PO₂) where saturation stays high, and a steep lower portion where small PO₂ drops cause dramatic desaturation. At PaO₂ of 60 mmHg (saturation ~90%), the patient is at the 'cliff edge' of the curve.": "",
  "A patient who lives at 4,000 meters altitude has a blood test showing elevated 2,3-BPG levels and a higher-than-normal hemoglobin concentration. Her physician explains these are compensatory adaptations. How does elevated 2,3-BPG help this patient tolerate high altitude?": "",
  "It decreases hemoglobin's O₂ affinity (right shift), promoting greater O₂ release to tissues despite the lower arterial PO₂": "",
  "It converts CO₂ to O₂ inside the red blood cells": "",
  "It directly increases the amount of dissolved O₂ in the plasma": "",
  "It increases hemoglobin's O₂ affinity so more O₂ is loaded at the lungs": "",
  "At high altitude, chronic hypoxia stimulates increased 2,3-BPG production in red blood cells. The elevated 2,3-BPG binds to deoxyhemoglobin and shifts the O₂-Hb curve rightward, ensuring that even though less O₂ is loaded at the lungs, more of what is loaded is released to the tissues.": "",
  "A student nurse observes a patient's nail beds turning blue (cyanosis). The attending physician explains that this is a sign of significant deoxygenation. Based on O₂ transport principles, approximately what SpO₂ level would typically be associated with visible central cyanosis?": "",
  "90-95% oxygen saturation on pulse oximetry": "",
  "Around 80-85% or lower, when deoxyhemoglobin exceeds ~5 g/dL in capillary blood": "",
  "95-100% oxygen saturation on pulse oximetry": "",
  "Any value below 99% oxygen saturation on pulse oximetry": "",
  "Central cyanosis typically becomes visible when the concentration of deoxygenated hemoglobin in capillary blood exceeds about 5 g/dL, which roughly corresponds to SpO₂ in the low 80s or below, though visibility depends on skin pigmentation and hemoglobin concentration.": "",
  "A blood bank technician is explaining to a nursing student why stored blood becomes less effective at delivering oxygen over time. The technician notes that 2,3-BPG levels decrease during storage. How does this affect the stored blood's ability to deliver oxygen?": "",
  "The stored blood becomes alkaline and cannot transport CO₂": "",
  "Low 2,3-BPG causes the blood to clot faster": "",
  "With lower 2,3-BPG, hemoglobin's O₂ affinity increases (left shift), so it holds onto O₂ more tightly and releases less to the tissues": "",
  "The hemoglobin degrades and can no longer bind O₂ at all": "",
  "During storage, red blood cells gradually lose 2,3-BPG. Without adequate 2,3-BPG, the O₂-Hb curve shifts leftward, meaning hemoglobin binds O₂ tightly and releases it poorly to tissues. It takes approximately 24 hours after transfusion for 2,3-BPG levels to normalize.": "",
  "A physician is treating a patient with severe metabolic acidosis (blood pH 7.15). She notes that the patient's O₂ saturation is lower than expected for his PaO₂. Using O₂ transport physiology, why does acidosis cause SpO₂ to appear lower than the PaO₂ would suggest?": "",
  "The pulse oximeter malfunctions in acidotic patients because the low pH alters the optical properties of hemoglobin and produces inaccurate infrared readings": "",
  "Acidosis causes the lungs to stop working because the low pH paralyzes the smooth muscle in the bronchial walls and prevents normal ventilation": "",
  "Acidosis destroys hemoglobin molecules in the blood through acid-mediated denaturation of the globin protein, reducing total oxygen-carrying capacity": "",
  "The Bohr effect — low pH causes a right shift of the O₂-Hb curve, reducing hemoglobin's affinity for O₂ and lowering saturation at any given PaO₂": "",
  "The Bohr effect explains that low pH (high H⁺) decreases hemoglobin's affinity for O₂ by promoting a right shift of the dissociation curve. At any given PaO₂, the hemoglobin will be less saturated than normal, which is why SpO₂ reads lower than expected.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a patient with sickle cell disease who presents with acute chest pain and dyspnea during a crisis. The student learns that sickle hemoglobin (HbS) polymerizes when deoxygenated, distorting the red blood cell into a rigid sickle shape. How does this affect O₂ transport?": "",
  "Sickled cells are destroyed prematurely (hemolysis), reducing total hemoglobin, and they obstruct small vessels, blocking O₂ delivery to tissues downstream": "",
  "HbS converts all O₂ to CO₂ inside the red blood cells": "",
  "Sickle cells release O₂ too quickly, causing O₂ toxicity in tissues": "",
  "HbS carries more O₂ than normal hemoglobin": "",
  "In sickle cell disease, HbS polymerizes under low O₂ conditions, causing RBCs to become rigid and sickle-shaped. These abnormal cells are fragile and lyse prematurely (causing chronic anemia), and their rigidity causes them to obstruct capillaries (vaso-occlusion), blocking blood flow and O₂ delivery to downstream tissues.": ""
}